{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_24","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"cat > .workflow/iphone-app-factory/adr.md <<'EOF'\n# ADR: WakeTask on SwiftAIBoilerplatePro\n\n- Status: Accepted\n- Date: 2026-05-14\n- Deciders: iPhone App Factory architecture consensus\n- Context: \"'`.workflow/iphone-app-factory/spec.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/definition-of-done.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/quality-bar.json`, architecture candidates in repository context\n\n## Decision\nWakeTask will be implemented by extending `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro` modules and composition boundaries, with no foundational module removals in MVP.\n\n## Decisions by Module\n1. `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro.xcodeproj`: retain as project root and scheme owner.\n2. `Config/App.xcconfig`: retain as configuration source of truth.\n3. `Packages/Core`: retain and extend for wake domain protocols/models.\n4. `Packages/Networking`: retain for non-critical remote data and telemetry.\n5. `Packages/Storage`: retain for persistent reliability timeline and alarm state.\n6. `Packages/Auth`: retain unchanged; optional for account-linked features.\n7. `Packages/Payments`: retain unchanged; supports transparent monetization.\n8. `Packages/AI`: retain unchanged; restricted to non-alarm-critical UX.\n9. `Packages/FeatureSettings`: retain and extend for context profiles and policy settings.\n10. `Packages/Localization`: retain for policy-safe and differentiated copy.\n11. `Packages/DesignSystem`: retain for 3:30am-safe interaction patterns.\n12. `CompositionRoot`: retain and extend for dependency injection and feature wiring.\n\n## Rationale\n- Satisfies explicit boilerplate-reuse constraints in spec and quality bar.\n- Minimizes delivery risk by reusing validated infra and CI assumptions.\n- Preserves App Store 4.3 differentiation by focusing changes on WakeTask-specific behavior (two-phase wake model, fallback safety rails, reliability telemetry) rather than generic foundation rewrites.\n\n## Dependency Order (required for any future removal proposal)\nAny proposal to remove a module must preserve this order and replace interfaces from the bottom up:\n1. `Core` protocol contracts remain stable first.\n2. Replace implementation adapters (`Storage`, `Networking`, `Auth`, `Payments`, `AI`) behind those contracts.\n3. Rebind in `CompositionRoot`.\n4. Validate UI consumers in `FeatureSettings`, `Localization`, `DesignSystem` surfaces.\n5. Re-run full quality gate and App Store language audit.\n\n## App Store 4.3 Consequences of Module Removal\nIf a module is removed or replaced without preserving differentiated WakeTask behavior:\n- Risk of clone-like implementation increases if UX degrades into generic alarm/paywall templates.\n- Loss of reliability logging or fallback transparency weakens differentiation claims and can trigger 4.3 scrutiny.\n- Replacing Localization/DesignSystem without policy controls increases risk of banned “guaranteed wake” or generic/derivative metadata language.\n- Removing Payments/Auth/AI foundations ad hoc can force rushed custom scaffolding that looks commodity and raises rejection risk during metadata + in-app review consistency checks.\n\n## Candidate Tradeoff Summary\n- Smallest-surface architecture bias is accepted for MVP speed and reduced regression area.\n- Extensible pipeline ideas are accepted only where they do not introduce new foundational frameworks or replace boilerplate modules.\n\n## Consequences\n- Positive: faster delivery, lower integration risk, cleaner audit trail for DoD and final review fanout.\n- Negative: some future extensibility is deferred to post-MVP ADRs.\n- Follow-up: any future module-removal or deep replacement requires a new ADR with migration plan, dependency-order proof, and explicit 4.3 impact analysis.\nEOF'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
